      "side": 1,
      "message": "Boy this is a confusing one.\n\ncanvas is an std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvasStack\u003e.  SkCanvasStack is an SkCanvas, but std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvasStack\u003e is not a std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvas\u003e.\n\nstd::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvas\u003e luckily has a constructor which takes a std::unique_ptr\u003cU\u003e\u0026\u0026 where U inherits from SkCanvas.  So std::move(canvas) to create a std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvasStack\u003e\u0026\u0026, which then triggers that non-explicit std::unique_ptr\u003cU\u003e\u0026\u0026 constructor for std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvas\u003e, with U \u003d\u003d SkCanvasStack.\n\nThis final value we return is an std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvas\u003e, which is an rvalue but not an rvalue reference, so I think _it_ can RVO.\n\nRead this as\n    return std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvas\u003e(std::move(canvas));\n\nor equivalently\n    return std::unique_ptr\u003cSkCanvas\u003e(canvas.release());\n\nor maybe also possibly the shorter but maybe more confusing\n    return { canvas.release(); }",
